<h2>English</h2>

<h3>Overview</h3>
<p>
This paper proposes <b>FedMerge</b>, a federated learning algorithm designed to improve robustness under highly heterogeneous (non-IID) client data distributions.
Instead of treating all client updates equally, FedMerge applies a <b>merge-inspired hierarchical clustering strategy</b> to group similar clients before global aggregation.
</p>

<p>
This work was submitted to the <b>2025 Korea Science and Engineering Fair (KSEF)</b> as an independent research project.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Methodology</h3>

<p>
FedMerge consists of four major components:
(1) L2 normalization of client weights,
(2) similarity measurement via Euclidean distance,
(3) merge-sort inspired hierarchical clustering,
and (4) distance–stage aware dynamic weighting.
</p>

<h4>Weight Normalization</h4>

$$
\omega_i' = \frac{\omega_i}{\|\omega_i\|_2}
$$

<p>
Each client update is normalized to remove magnitude bias caused by heterogeneous data distributions.
</p>

<h4>Similarity Measurement</h4>

$$
d(i,j) = \|\omega_i' - \omega_j'\|_2
$$

<p>
Pairwise Euclidean distance is used to quantify similarity between client updates.
</p>

<h4>Dynamic Weight Assignment</h4>

$$
\alpha = e^{-\lambda d} \cdot \gamma^s
$$

<p>
Where:
<ul>
<li><b>d</b> = merge distance between clusters</li>
<li><b>s</b> = merge stage (earlier merges receive higher influence)</li>
<li><b>\(\lambda, \gamma\)</b> = hyperparameters controlling distance and stage sensitivity</li>
</ul>
</p>

<p>
Clusters that merge earlier and have smaller distances contribute more strongly to the global update.
</p>

<h4>Global Aggregation</h4>

$$
\theta_{global} = \sum_k \alpha_k \cdot \theta_k
$$

<p>
Cluster-aware weighting reduces client drift and stabilizes convergence.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Experimental Setup</h3>

<ul>
<li><b>Environment:</b> Google Colab Pro (NVIDIA A100 / High-performance CPU)</li>
<li><b>Framework:</b> PyTorch 2.x, NumPy, SciPy, scikit-learn</li>
<li><b>Datasets:</b> CIFAR-10, CIFAR-100, FEMNIST</li>
<li><b>Clients:</b> 30–100 depending on dataset</li>
<li><b>Baselines:</b> FedAvg, FedProx, SCAFFOLD</li>
<li><b>Metrics:</b> Test Accuracy, Convergence Stability</li>
</ul>

