<p>
FedMerge demonstrated especially strong improvements under severe non-IID conditions, 
with the largest gain (+8.3%) observed on CIFAR-100.
Convergence variance was reduced by up to 40% compared to FedAvg, 
leading to smoother and more stable training dynamics.
</p>

<hr>

<h3>Conclusion</h3>

<p>
FedMerge introduces a similarity-aware hierarchical clustering mechanism into federated aggregation.
By explicitly modeling client similarity and incorporating merge-stage information,
the algorithm mitigates client drift and stabilizes training under heterogeneous data distributions.
</p>

<p>
The results suggest that incorporating structural similarity among clients
is an effective strategy for addressing the non-IID problem in federated learning.
</p>

